The tide-generating potential varies as the square of the distance from the earth’s centre, and the corresponding forces act at every point throughout its mass. No solid matter possesses the property of absolute rigidity, and we must therefore admit the probable existence of tidal elastic deformation of the solid earth. The problem of finding the state of strain of an elastic sphere under given stresses was first solved by Lamé;
I ThéorieMath, de ΓElasticité, 1866, p. 213. he made, however, but few physical deductions from his solution. An independent solution was found by Sir W. Thomson,
Thomson and Tait, Nat. Phil., §§ 732-737 and 833-842, or Phil. Trans., pt. ii., 1863, p. 583. who drew some interesting conclusions concerning the earth.
